# SOLID File Size and Decomposition Rule

When implementing features, avoid long files. Prefer small, focused modules that follow SOLID.

## Core Requirements

- Keep each file focused on one responsibility.
- Split classes/functions when one module starts handling multiple concerns.
- Prefer composition over deep inheritance.
- Depend on abstractions (interfaces/types), not concrete implementations.
- Extract reusable logic into dedicated modules instead of duplicating code.

## Practical Guidance

- Aim for small files (roughly under 200 lines unless justified).
- If a file grows quickly, break it into:
  - domain logic
  - orchestration/service layer
  - adapters/integration code
  - validation/parsing helpers
- Avoid "god" services that do data access, business rules, and formatting in one place.

## Example

```typescript
// ❌ BAD: one file handles validation + business logic + API formatting
// ✅ GOOD: split into user-validator.ts, user-service.ts, user-presenter.ts
```
